Dear Canada General Warranty Inc. and Sean, 
I am writing to formally dispute the partial payout issued under my GAP insurance policy (#230707) for the vehicle I financed through Scotia Bank and insured with Aviva. The payout does not fulfill the obligations outlined in the GAP insurance agreement, leaving me with an unjust financial burden. I am extremely frustrated by this situation, as I was led to believe that GAP insurance would fully cover the remaining balance of my loan in the event of a total loss.
Here are the details for your reference:
Vehicle Purchased: 2022 Hyundai Elantra Preferred
Purchase Date: March 2, 2024
Financed Amount: $43,273.40 at 7.99% interest over 8 years (biweekly payments of $282.24)
Dealership: Autovilla Car Sales
GAP Insurance Provider: Canada General Warranty Inc.
GAP Policy Number: 230707
Accident Date: June 5, 2024
Collision Report Number: ACC-503781389
When I purchased the vehicle from Autovilla Car Sales, I was assured by sales representative Ammy Randhawa that the GAP insurance policy would cover any remaining balance on my car loan in the event of a total loss. This assurance played a critical role in my decision to purchase GAP insurance from your company on the day of sale.
After my accident, my primary insurer, Aviva (Policy #A97182630PLA), issued a settlement of $25,047.22. This left an outstanding loan balance of $18,151.07. I submitted all required documentation to Canada General Warranty Inc., yet only $9,800.87 was paid toward the remaining balance, leaving a shortfall of $8,350.20 that I am now responsible for.
When I inquired about this shortfall, your representative, Mr. Sean Terkildsen, explained that the decision was based on the car’s "Adjusted Cash Value." This explanation undermines the fundamental purpose of GAP insurance, which is to protect consumers from financial hardship by covering the "gap" between the insurance settlement and the remaining loan balance. Your company’s refusal to cover the full balance completely contradicts the expectations set at the time of purchase.
GAP insurance is not based on subjective vehicle valuation but on the financial gap caused by depreciation and the loan terms. By failing to pay the full balance, your company is effectively denying the very coverage I paid for and misrepresenting the purpose of the product.
I am deeply frustrated by this situation and believe it to be both unethical and a breach of the agreement. If the remaining balance of $8,350.20 is not paid in full within 14 days, I will have no choice but to escalate this matter further.
I will file a consumer complaint through the court system.
I will bring this matter to the attention of the Financial Services Regulatory Authority of Ontario (FSRA) for a full investigation into your practices.
I will pursue legal action against Autovilla Car Sales (Attn: Ammy Randhawa) if the dealership’s assurances about GAP insurance coverage were inaccurate or misleading.
This situation has caused me undue stress and financial strain. I expect Canada General Warranty Inc. to honor the full coverage of the GAP insurance policy I purchased in good faith. Failure to do so will not only damage your reputation but also expose you to legal and regulatory consequences.
I urge you to review this case immediately and resolve it without further delay.
I am also cc’ing Aviva Canada (my primary insurer) and Autovilla Car Sales (Attn: Ammy Randhawa) to ensure all parties involved are aware of this situation.
I look forward to your prompt response and resolution.
Sincerely,
Dilraj Singh Sandhu
